8-08-02 03:52:53','',0,'https://codejoy.blog/2018/08/02/blog-personal/',0,'custom_css','',0),(137,3,'2018-08-16 01:49:39','2018-08-16 01:49:39','','Documents','','inherit','open','closed','','documents','','','2018-08-16 01:49:39','2018-08-16 01:49:39','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Documents-1.zip',0,'attachment','application/zip',0),(139,3,'2018-08-16 01:50:48','2018-08-16 01:50:48','','purple striped background','','inherit','open','closed','','copy-of-copy-of-background','','','2018-08-16 01:50:48','2018-08-16 01:50:48','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Copy-of-Copy-of-Background-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(140,3,'2018-08-16 01:51:49','2018-08-16 01:51:49','','Logo','','inherit','open','closed','','logo-3','','','2018-08-16 01:51:49','2018-08-16 01:51:49','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Logo-3-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(141,3,'2018-08-16 01:57:01','2018-08-16 01:57:01','','Copy of Copy of Copy of Background','','inherit','open','closed','','copy-of-copy-of-copy-of-background','','','2018-08-16 01:57:01','2018-08-16 01:57:01','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Background-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(143,3,'2018-08-17 04:27:30','2018-08-17 04:27:30','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Notes on what I learned from video \"CSS Selectors\" from the <a href=\"https://www.udemy.com/the-complete-web-developer-in-2018/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">The Complete Web Developer in 2018: Zero to Mastery class on Udemy</a></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>What are CSS selectors and why should I care?</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CSS selectors are the part of CSS that actually select the part of the html code that you want to apply style to. In order to change something with CSS, you need to know what selector to use to grab the thing you want to change!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>element1, element2      </strong>Applies style to both elements</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"left\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><strong>element1 element2       </strong>Applies style to all element2s that are within element1s (for example, if it was \'p li\', it would apply the style to all lists that are within paragraphs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<hr>\n<p><strong>element1 &gt; element2&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Applies style to all element2s that are parents of element1s</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<div class=\"htmlCode\">\n<h5 class=\"htmlTitle\">html:</h5>\n<p>&lt;h2&gt;My thoughts on CSS&lt;/h2&gt;<br>&lt;div&gt;<br>&lt;p&gt;CSS is really cool.<br>&lt;/div&gt;</p>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"cssCode\">\n<h5 class=\"cssTitle\">css:</h5>\n<p>h2 &gt; p {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; color: #AA4139;<br>}</p>\n<p></p>\n</div>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><em><br>In this example, the CSS style will not be applied because div (not h2) is the parent of p. If we wanted the code to apply to p, we would need to change h2 &gt; p to div &gt; p</em></p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><!-- wp:separator -->\n</p>\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\">\n<!-- /wp:separator --><p></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><strong><br>.class &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Can be used to apply style to a subset of an element. Can be applied multiple times throughout the html document.</p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<div class=\"htmlCode\">\n<h5 class=\"htmlTitle\">html:</h5>\n<p>&lt;p class=\"exampleclass\"&gt;Example paragraph would be red.&lt;/p&gt;<br>&lt;p class=\"exampleclass\"&gt;Example paragraph would be red.&lt;/p&gt;<br>&lt;p class=\"exampleclass extra\"&gt;Example paragraph would be purple.&lt;/p&gt;</p>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"cssCode\">\n<h5 class=\"cssTitle\">css:</h5>\n<p>.exampleclass {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; color: red;<br>}</p>\n<p>.extra {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; color: purple;<br>}</p>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<hr>\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>#id</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Similar to class, but can be used only once throughout the html document.</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<div class=\"htmlCode\">\n<h5 class=\"htmlTitle\">html:</h5>\n<p>&lt;div id=\"div1\"&gt;Example would be blue&lt;/div&gt;</p>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"cssCode\">\n<h5 class=\"cssTitle\">css:</h5>\n<p>#div1 {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; background: blue;<br>}</p>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<hr>\n<p></p>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><strong>* &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Applies style to everything (unless the element has been overridden with another selector)<br>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><strong><br>:hover&nbsp;</strong> &nbsp; Applies style to the element(s) on mouse hover</p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<div class=\"cssCode\">\n<h5 class=\"cssTitle\">css:</h5>\n<p>h2, p:hover {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; color: red;<br>}</p>\n</div>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><strong><br>.webtext:last-child&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>Applies style to the last child of the set</p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><strong>.webtext:first-child&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Applies style to the first child of the set</p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p></p>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>!important&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>Will override ALL other formatting (use not recommended)</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<div class=\"htmlCode\">\n<h5 class=\"htmlTitle\">html:</h5>\n<p>&lt;p&gt;This paragraph will be pink, despite the last selector indicating that it should be blue.&lt;/p&gt;</p>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<div class=\"cssCode\">\n<h5 class=\"cssTitle\">css:</h5>\n<p>p {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; color: pink !important;<br>}</p>\n<p>p {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; color: blue;<br>}</p>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<hr>\n<p></p>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p>What selectors win out in the cascade depends on:</p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><!-- wp:list --></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Specificity (higher specificity given priority)</li>\n<li>Importance</li>\n<li>Source Order</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n<!-- /wp:list --></p>\n<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://specificity.keegan.st/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Click here</a> for a cool Specificity calculator!</p>\n<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>','CSS selectors','','publish','open','open','','css-selectors','','','2018-09-23 00:21:11','2018-09-23 00:21:11','',0,'https://codejoy.blog/?p=143',0,'post','',0),(194,3,'2018-08-19 18:14:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Notes on what I learned from video “Flexbox” from the <a href=\"https://www.udemy.com/the-complete-web-developer-in-2018/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">The Complete Web Developer in 2018: Zero to Mastery class on Udemy</a></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Defining a flex container (enables flex content for all its direct children):</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>.container {\n    display: flex;\n}\n\nOR\n\n.container {\n    display: inline-flex;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Flexbox','','draft','open','open','','','','','2018-08-19 18:14:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://codejoy.blog/?p=194',0,'post','',0),(213,3,'2018-08-19 18:38:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Bootstrap','','draft','open','open','','','','','2018-08-19 18:38:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://www.kandisflick.wpengine.com/?p=213',0,'post','',0),(215,3,'2018-08-19 20:54:24','2018-08-20 03:54:24','','andressa-voltolini-202193-unsplash','','inherit','open','closed','','andressa-voltolini-202193-unsplash','','','2018-08-19 20:54:24','2018-08-20 03:54:24','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/andressa-voltolini-202193-unsplash-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(216,3,'2018-08-19 20:54:34','2018-08-20 03:54:34','','andressa-voltolini-202193-unsplash','','inherit','open','closed','','andressa-voltolini-202193-unsplash-2','','','2018-08-19 20:54:34','2018-08-20 03:54:34','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/andressa-voltolini-202193-unsplash-1-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(219,3,'2018-08-23 22:38:00','2018-08-24 05:38:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Notes on what I learned from the JavaScript section of <a href=\"https://www.udemy.com/the-complete-web-developer-in-2018/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">The Complete Web Developer in 2018: Zero to Mastery class on Udemy</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Q: What is JavaScript?<br/>A: It\'s the programming language that makes things happen on the website you visit. Pop-ups, replying to a Facebook post, tweeting, posting a YouTube video… ALL JavaScript!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customTextColor\":\"#f1e8e8\",\"backgroundColor\":\"vivid-cyan-blue\"} -->\n<p style=\"color:#f1e8e8\" class=\"has-background has-vivid-cyan-blue-background-color\"><em>Cool fact: JavaScript was created by Netscape in an effort to give it a competitive advantage. (bonus points: who actually remembers Netscape? If you don\'t know what it is, go google it. RIP Netscape.)<br/></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>JavaScript Types <span style=\"display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: transparent; color: rgb(50, 55, 60); cursor: text; font-family: Noto Serif,serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">(values that JavaScript can have)</span></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Number: </strong>Integers like 1, 2, 3, or math like 1 + 2 (returns 3) or 6 / 2 (returns 3). There\'s also something called a modulo calculation, which I\'ve explained below if you\'re unfamiliar with the concept (I was super confused by it when I first saw it).<br/></span><br style=\"background-color: transparent; box-sizing: border-box; color: #32373c; font-family: Noto Serif,serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\"/><em>Note: % = Modulo. Modulo is a calculation of what is remaining after you divide one number by another. So 3 % 2 = 1, because if you divide 3 by 2, you end up with 1 left over. 12 % 6 = 0, because 12 is able to be divided up into two buckets of 6, with nothing remaining.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<p><strong>2. String:</strong> Text, indicated by putting something in single or double quotes. \"hello world\" \'bob\', \"Hello \" + \"there\" returns \"Hello there\" (don\'t forget the space after the \'o\'!). You can also turn numbers into strings: \"3\".<br/><br/><em>Note: If your string contains a quote, there are a couple ways to handle it:<br/>a) Use double quotes on the outside, and single quotes on the inside: \"This isn\'t going to return an error.\"<br/>b) Use a backslash (\\) to indicate that the single quote within the string should not be considered code: \'This isn\\\'t going to return an error.\' (The \\ doesn\'t print)<br/><br/></em>Performing calculations with strings:<br/><br/><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Example 1: Adding a number and a \"number\" (a number with type equal to string)</span><div class=\"code\"><p class=\"input\">Input: 10 + \"34\"</p><p class=\"correctOutput\">Output: \"1034\"</p></div><br/>Why? JavaScript looks at the input (10) and sees that you\'re trying to add it to a string, so it makes the entire thing a string to make it work. So if you added \"SillyBilly\" + \"34\", you\'d get \"SillyBilly34\". It\'s treating the 10 like SillyBilly (a string).<br/><br/><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Example 2: Subtracting a \"number\" from a number</span><br/><div class=\"code\"><p class=\"input\">Input: 10 - \"3\"<br/><p class=\"correctOutput\">Output: 7</div>Q: What the heck?! Why is subtraction treated differently than addition? Why JavaScript gods, WHY?!<br/>A: Sometimes the gods have a reason. Have a little faith. The reason is this - while you <strong>can</strong> add two strings together (i.e. \"hello \" + \"there\" = \"hello there\"), you can\'t really subtract a string from another string. Because of this, JavaScript helpfully(?) decides to subtract 3 as a number rather than return an error, because it assumes you know what you\'re doing (a dangerous assumption in my case, but thanks for the vote of confidence, JavaScript gods!).</p>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3.<strong> Boolean: </strong>True/False (example: 3 > 4 would return False, 3 >= 3 would return True)<br/>Examples:<br/></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns has-2-columns\"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"backgroundColor\":\"luminous-vivid-amber\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-background has-luminous-vivid-amber-background-color\"><strong>Input</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#f7d77c\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#f7d77c\" class=\"has-background\">5 > 10<br/>5 &lt; 10<br/>5 &lt;= 5<br/>2 = 2<br/>2 === 2 (does 2 equal 2?)<br/>3 !== 3 (is 3 not equal to 3?)<br/></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"backgroundColor\":\"pale-cyan-blue\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-background has-pale-cyan-blue-background-color\"><strong>Output</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#c0e3fd\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#c0e3fd\" class=\"has-background\">False<br/>True<br/>True<br/>Error<br/>True<br/>False<br/></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Q: Ok, I\'m with you, except for the triple equal signs. What\'s up with that?<br/>A: I\'m actually not sure. I\'ve seen double equal signs used in Python, but this is my first time seeing triple. I\'ll come back and explain it when I understand it. All I know for now is that if you want to ask if something is equal to another thing in JavaScript, you need to use triple equal signs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><span style=\"display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: transparent; color: #23282d; cursor: text; font-family: Noto Serif,serif; font-size: 31.2px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">JavaScript Variables</span></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Variable rules:</strong><br/>1) Must start with a letter, underscore or dollar sign (cannot be a number or any other symbol)<br/>2) Variable names should be in camel case (exampleVariable, newBook, badApple)<br/></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Example of using variables with prompts:</span><br/><div class=\"code\"><p class=\"input\">var currentJob = prompt(\"Enter your current job title\");<br/>var dreamJob = prompt(\"Enter your dream job title\");</div></p>User is prompted and inputs: \"Teacher\" and \"Web Developer\"<br/></p>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After user has input:<br/><div class=\"code\">\n<p class=\"input\">Input: currentJob<br/></p>\n<p class=\"correctOutput\">Output: \"Teacher\"<br/></p>\n<p class=\"input\">Input: dreamJob<br/></p>\n<p class=\"correctOutput\">Output: \"Web Developer\"</p></div>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<p><br/><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Another example, this time with numbers input as variable values:</span><br/><div class=\"code\"><p class=\"input\">var luckyNumber = prompt(\"What is your lucky number?\");<br/>var unluckyNumber = prompt(\"What is your least lucky number?\")</div></p>User is prompted and inputs: \"5\" and \"2\"<br/><br/>After user has input:<br/><div class=\"code\"><p class=\"input\">Input: luckyNumber</p><p class=\"correctOutput\">Output: \"5\"</p><br/><p class=\"input\">Input: unluckyNumber</p><p class=\"correctOutput\">Output: \"2\"</p>(See the quotes? Those are strings!)</div><br><strong>In order to turn a string back into a number, we\'d change the Type:<div class=\"code\"></strong><p class=\"input\">Input: Number(luckyNumber)</p><p class=\"correctOutput\">Output: 5</p></strong></div><strong>Add the numbers together:<div class=\"code\"></strong>var sum = Number(luckyNumber) + Number(unluckyNumber)</div><strong>Return the sum to the user:<div class=\"code\"></strong>alert(sum);</div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','JavaScript Types & Variables','','publish','open','open','','the-basics-of-javascript','','','2018-08-23 22:38:00','2018-08-24 05:38:00','',0,'https://www.kandisflick.wpengine.com/?p=219',0,'post','',0),(226,3,'2018-08-23 22:44:42','2018-08-24 05:44:42','body {\n    color: #712fff;\n}\n\nh1 {\n    color: #712fff;\n		font-weight: bold;\n		font-style: italic;\n				\n}\n\nh3 {\n	color: #ffbd4a;\n	font-weight: bold;\n}\n\nh4 {\n	color: #351677;\n	font-weight: bold;\n	font-style: italic;\n}\n\nh5 {\n	font-variant: small-caps;\n	font-size: 25px\n}\n\np {\n    color:black;\n}\n\n.htmlCode {\n	background-color: rgba(255, 252, 222, .25);\n	border: 2px dotted;\n	border-color: rgba(255, 252, 222, .5);\n	margin-left: 50px;\n	margin-right: 50px\n\n}\n\n.htmlTitle {\n	color: turquoise;\n}\n\n.cssCode {\n	background-color: rgba(184, 197, 209, .25);\n	border: 2px dotted;\n	border-color: rgba(95, 195, 204, .5);\n	margin-left: 50px;\n	margin-right: 50px\n}\n\n.cssTitle {\n	color: #DA1B79;\n}\n\n\n\n\n','ashe','','publish','closed','closed','','ashe','','','2018-08-23 22:44:42','2018-08-24 05:44:42','',0,'https://www.kandisflick.wpengine.com/2018/08/23/ashe/',0,'custom_css','',0),(235,3,'2018-08-23 22:58:19','2018-08-24 05:58:19','','woman typing','woman typing','inherit','open','closed','','woman-typing','','','2018-08-23 22:58:19','2018-08-24 05:58:19','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/woman-typing-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(236,3,'2018-08-23 22:59:13','2018-08-24 05:59:13','','cropped-woman-typing.jpg','','inherit','open','closed','','cropped-woman-typing-jpg','','','2018-08-23 22:59:13','2018-08-24 05:59:13','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/cropped-woman-typing-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(238,3,'2018-08-23 23:01:45','2018-08-24 06:01:45','','Code on a screen','Code on a screen','inherit','open','closed','','code-on-a-screen','','','2018-08-23 23:01:45','2018-08-24 06:01:45','',0,'http://ka