08-30 08:39:03','2018-08-30 15:39:03','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/cropped-Rainbow-Woman-Logo-1-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(338,3,'2018-08-30 08:39:35','2018-08-30 15:39:35','','cropped-rawpixel-600782-unsplash-2.jpg','','inherit','open','closed','','cropped-rawpixel-600782-unsplash-2-jpg','','','2018-08-30 08:39:35','2018-08-30 15:39:35','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/cropped-rawpixel-600782-unsplash-2-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(343,3,'2018-08-30 09:11:39','2018-08-30 16:11:39','','CSS','','inherit','open','closed','','css','','','2018-08-30 09:11:39','2018-08-30 16:11:39','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CSS-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(344,3,'2018-08-30 09:16:09','2018-08-30 16:16:09','','JavaScript Conditionals & Operators','','inherit','open','closed','','javascript-conditionals-operators-2','','','2018-08-30 09:16:09','2018-08-30 16:16:09','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/JavaScript-Conditionals-Operators-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(346,3,'2018-08-30 09:19:30','2018-08-30 16:19:30','','JavaScript Types & Variables','','inherit','open','closed','','javascript-types-variables','','','2018-08-30 09:19:30','2018-08-30 16:19:30','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/JavaScript-Types-Variables-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(349,3,'2018-08-31 20:59:15','2018-09-01 03:59:15','<p>Functions are the fun part of JavaScript!</p>\n<p>What are functions? They are pieces of code that perform actions. Without functions, JavaScript wouldn\'t really do anything.</p>\n<p>If you\'ve been following along with me in previous posts, you already know some functions! For example, these are functions:</p>\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">alert()\nprompt()</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note: The () next to the function names mean to execute (also called \'run\' or \'call\') the function.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When using functions, we can either <strong>use existing JavaScript functions</strong>, or <strong>create our own functions.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer -->\n<div style=\"height:100px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>\n\nHow to create a function<br/></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1) Function Declaration</strong><br/><br/>Declare/create the function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">function sayHello() {\n    console.log(\"Hello\");\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nCall the function:\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">sayHello();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer -->\n<div style=\"height:100px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2) Function Expression</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Assign a function to the sayBye variable:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted {\"className\":\".code\"} -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted .code\">var sayBye = function() {\n    console.log(\"Bye\");\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use variable to call the function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">sayBye();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note: When using this, the function itself doesn\'t actually have a name. The function has simply been assigned to a variable (sayBye). This is called using an Anonymous Function.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Rather than using an anonymous function, we could have done this instead:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">var sayBye = function byebye() {<br/>    console.log(\"Bye\");<br/>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This would have created a function called \'byebye\'.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><em>Examples of declaring and calling functions</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Declare the function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">function sing() {<br/>    console.log(\"AHHHHHHH\");<br/>    console.log(\"TEEEEEEE\");<br/>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Call the function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">sing();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this case, if I wanted to later change the song being sung by this function, I\'d have to manually type it in and change the function. That would be tiresome.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><em>A better way to do it</em><br/></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nDeclare the function:\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">function sing(song) {<br/>    console.log(song);<br/>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, any time I want to change the song, I can type:<br/>Input:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">sing(\"I\'m just a girl\");<br/>sing(\"I\'d rather not be\");<br/>sing(\"Cuz they won\'t let me drive late at night\");</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Output:<br/></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">I\'m just a girl<br/>I\'d rather not be<br/>Cuz they won\'t let me drive late at night\n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><em>Another example</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Declare the function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">function multiply(a, b) {<br/>    return a * b;<br/>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Input:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">multiply(5, 10);</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Output:<br/></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">50\n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note:</em> <em>\'Return\' is how we get the function to give us something, rather than just log the result in the console. Once you return in a function, the function stops running.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><em>Using IF statements in functions</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Declare the function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">function multiply(a, b) {<br/>    if (a > 10 || b > 10) {<br/>        return \"that\'s too hard\";<br/>    } else {<br/>        return a * b;<br/>    }<br/>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Input:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">multiply(5, 10);</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nOutput:\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">\"that\'s too hard\"</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Congrats, you\'ve made it through learning functions. The best way to become competent with functions is to keep playing with them. Functions may be the hardest part of JavaScript, but they are also where the fun is! Make sure you get a good understanding of functions before moving on to the next topic.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','JavaScript Functions','Functions are the hardest thing you\'ll learn in JavaScript.','publish','open','open','','javascript-functions','','','2018-08-31 20:59:15','2018-09-01 03:59:15','',0,'https://www.kandisflick.wpengine.com/?p=349',0,'post','',0),(359,3,'2018-08-31 21:37:37','2018-09-01 04:37:37','','joshua-coleman-655076-unsplash','','inherit','open','closed','','joshua-coleman-655076-unsplash','','','2018-08-31 21:37:37','2018-09-01 04:37:37','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/joshua-coleman-655076-unsplash-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(360,3,'2018-08-31 21:39:33','2018-09-01 04:39:33','','david-hofmann-574523-unsplash','','inherit','open','closed','','david-hofmann-574523-unsplash','','','2018-08-31 21:39:33','2018-09-01 04:39:33','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/david-hofmann-574523-unsplash-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(363,3,'2018-08-31 21:46:30','2018-09-01 04:46:30','','julie-johnson-666385-unsplash','','inherit','open','closed','','julie-johnson-666385-unsplash','','','2018-08-31 21:46:30','2018-09-01 04:46:30','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/julie-johnson-666385-unsplash-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(364,3,'2018-08-31 21:50:03','2018-09-01 04:50:03','','caspar-rubin-224229-unsplash','','inherit','open','closed','','caspar-rubin-224229-unsplash','','','2018-08-31 21:50:03','2018-09-01 04:50:03','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/caspar-rubin-224229-unsplash-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(366,3,'2018-08-31 21:51:55','2018-09-01 04:51:55','','kamil-s-738524-unsplash','','inherit','open','closed','','kamil-s-738524-unsplash','','','2018-08-31 21:51:55','2018-09-01 04:51:55','',0,'http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/kamil-s-738524-unsplash-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(378,3,'2018-09-12 21:37:01','2018-09-13 04:37:01','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>HTML (short for Hypertext Markup Language) is what web designers use to mark up and describe the parts on a web page so that your browser can read the website correctly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note: This is a summary of what I learned from the HTML section of the <a href=\"http://www.skillcrush.com\" target=\"_blank\">Skillcrush</a> 101 course.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>How do you write HTML?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>HTML is made up of <strong>tags</strong> that are used to describe the different parts of a web page. Once you understand HTML tags, you can use them to build a web page!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<h4 style=\"text-align:center\">Summary of MITs (Most Important Tags)<br/></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note: <strong>Metatag </strong>means <strong>data about data.</strong> These are tags that contain information that isn\'t actually seen by the user. The content within these tags is used by the browser to help it read the html document.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5><em>Must-haves</em> (meaning you need them on your site for the web browser to have any idea of what it\'s looking at)<br/></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>&lt;!doctype html>     </strong><em>Metatag</em><br/>Tells the browser what type of document it\'s reading.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;html> &lt;/html>    </strong>  <em>Metatag</em><br/>Denotes the HTML portion of the document.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;head> &lt;/head> </strong><em>     Metatag </em><br/>Denotes the head area of your site. This is where you\'ll find things like:<ul><li><strong>&lt;title> &lt;/title></strong>      <em>Metatag        (also a must-have!)</em><br/>This is what shows up on the tab on the browser bar<br/><br/></li><li><strong>Other Metatags</strong><ul><li><strong></strong><strong>&lt;script> &lt;/script>     </strong><em>Metatag</em><br/>Contains the link to the JavaScript file(s) used on the site. </li><li><strong>&lt;link />    </strong> <em>Metatag<br/></em>Links to stylesheets (which contain the CSS that the site uses) <br/><br/></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>&lt;body> &lt;/body></strong> <em>     Metatag</em><br/>Denotes the body area of the document. This is where your content will reside, and it will be visible to the user.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Structural tags - not <em>must-have</em> (but they definitely are if you want your site to look beautiful).</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>&lt;div> &lt;/div></strong><br/>Used to divide up different parts of your website. This tag is especially useful for CSS design.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;header> &lt;/header></strong><br/>Used for site headers and navigation.<br/><ul><li><strong>&lt;nav> &lt;/nav></strong><br/>Used for site navigation, typically with unordered list items (see next)<br/><br/></li></ul></li><li><strong>&lt;ul> &lt;/ul></strong> and <strong>&lt;ol> &lt;/ol></strong><br/>Denotes an unordered list (ul) or an ordered list (ol).<br/><ul><li><strong>&lt;li> &lt;/li></strong><br/>Denotes a list item. If the list items are nested within <strong>&lt;ul> &lt;/ul></strong> tags, they will be bullets (like the list you\'re currently reading). If the list items are nested within <strong>&lt;ol> &lt;/ol></strong> tags, they will be numbered (AKA \"ordered\").<br/><br/></li></ul></li><li><strong>&lt;section> &lt;/section></strong><br/>Denotes major sections of your site.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;article> &lt;/article></strong><br/>Used for complete blocks of content such as blog posts or news articles.<br/><br/></li><li>&lt;<strong>aside></strong> <strong>&lt;/aside></strong><br/>Used to - you guessed it! - set content aside. This tag is usually used for sidebars.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;footer> &lt;/footer><br/></strong>Indicates the footer of the site. You\'ll usually find copyright information and social media links here.<br/></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Text tags - used to make your text look different.</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>&lt;p> &lt;/p></strong><br/>Denotes a paragraph<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;h1> &lt;/h1><br/></strong>Biggest header<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;h2> &lt;/h2></strong><br/>Second biggest header<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;h3> &lt;/h3><br/></strong>Third... okay, you get the idea. Goes all the way down to <strong>&lt;h6> &lt;/h6><br/><br/></strong></li><li><strong>&lt;strong> &lt;/strong><br/></strong>Makes text <strong>bold.<br/><br/></strong></li><li><strong>&lt;em> &lt;/em><br/></strong>Makes text <em>italic</em>.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;br><br/></strong>Used to create a break between two parts of text.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Content tags - used to bring in content from outside sources</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>&lt;img></strong><br/>Used to add images to your site.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;iframe></strong><br/>Allows you to embed another document (like a YouTube video or Google map) into your site.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;a> &lt;/a></strong><br/>Adds links to other pages.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>&lt;span> &lt;/span></strong><br/>Gives you a way to group content on your site.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":25} -->\n<div style=\"height:25px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>HTML tags are really all you need to know in order to write HTML code! If you get familiar with these tags and how to use them, you can create a basic website.<br/><br/>Want to make your website\'s text pretty? <a href=\"http://kandisflick.wpengine.com/2018/08/17/css-selectors/\">Check out my post on CSS.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','What is HTML?','','publish','open','open','','what-is-html','','','2018-09-12 21:37:01','2018-09-13 04:37:01','',0,'https://www.kandisflick.wpengine.com/?p=378',0,'post','',0),(380,3,'2018-09-21 19: